sec.p:
Combining P-values (CP): we use the standard meta-analysis process of combining p-values. Specifically, here we employ the classical Fisher combination method [34]. Benjamini [35]: Benjamini and Heller proposed a method for testing whether at least u out of n partial null-hypotheses are false. Their method is valid also when some specific dependency structures hold among the partial p-values, and the global p-value is computed as:
λBenjamini(u,n)=minj=1,…,n−u+1⁡{(n−u+1)jλ(u−1+j)}
where the partial p-values λj have been ordered so that λj ≤ λj+1. When u = 1, the null hypotheses of the Benjamini and NPC method coincide. Interestingly, for u = 1 the Benjamini equation reduces to the Benjamini-Hochberg formula for controlling the false discovery rate [36].
